article.description: Alana Beard had 20 points and a career-high six assists to lead the Washington Mystics to a 67-63 overtime victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Sanford (13 boards) scores game-winning layup
article.linkText: Beard's 20 points lead Mystics to OT win
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rookie Alana Beard has looked like a seasoned
veteran ever since the Washington Mystics put teammate Chamique
Holdsclaw on the injured list.

The Mystics' new go-to player had 20 points, a career-high six
assists, four rebounds and four steals in Washington's 67-63
overtime victory over the Sacramento Monarchs.

"We worked entirely too hard that entire game to let it slip
away," Beard said. "I think the team did a great job of pulling
together and getting it done in the second half. Then in overtime,
we set the tone."

Stacey Dales-Schuman hit a 3-pointer to open overtime for
Washington. Nakia Sanford, who grabbed a career-high 13 rebounds
for the Mystics, scored the game-winning layup with 1:34 left.

Murriel Page made two free throws with 6 seconds remaining to
seal the first victory for the Mystics (13-16) since the WNBA's
Olympic break.

"I don't think it came down to my free throws," Page said.
"Chasity Melvin's play is what got us there."

The setback ended a four-game winning streak by the Monarchs
(15-14), who were led by Kara Lawson's 14 points. Tangela Smith and
DeMya Walker each added 10.

Page and Stacey Dales-Schuman both scored 10 points for
Washington.

Beard was 9-for-21 from the field, but still is waiting for her
best WNBA performance.

"No, haven't had it yet," she said.

"Alana is a big-game player," Monarchs guard Ticha Penicheiro
said. "I am a fan of hers. She is very aggressive. She has great
instincts that will make her a key player in this league."

Beard hopes that Holdsclaw, who has missed three games because
of an undisclosed health issue, will return Thursday against the
New York Liberty, the Eastern Conference leaders.

"If she decides to play then I'm really definitely going to
welcome her back, as will everyone on the team," said Beard, the
second player selected in this year's draft. "She's our teammate,
and it's an added body to the team. We could definitely use it.
Anytime 'Mique comes back that's a guaranteed 30 (points)."

Page drew a charge on Penicheiro with 30 seconds remaining in
regulation and the score tied at 58. Beard missed a jumper with 6
seconds left, and Sanford missed a follow with 3 seconds on the
clock. Melvin then missed two free throws with 2 seconds left,
sending the game into overtime.

Penicheiro's two free throws and two more by Walker gave the
Monarchs a 58-54 lead with 3:06 left in regulation. Melvin made
consecutive layups to tie it at 58 with 2:11 to play.

Melvin's three-point play gave Washington a 39-34 halftime lead.
